uld find the active class called `Serialization` and then generate a corresponding `SerializationTest`. That could be a good approach! I’ll need to finalize this thought.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"Implemented coverage for `jersey.repackaged.com.google.common.collect.Serialization`.\\n\\nChanges made:\\n- Added dedicated test file:\\n  - `tests/src/org.glassfish.jersey.bundles.repackaged/jersey-guava/2.23.2/src/test/java/org_glassfish_jersey_bundles_repackaged/jersey_guava/SerializationTest.java`\\n- The test round-trips an `ArrayListMultimap` through standard Java serialization, naturally exercising:\\n  - `Serialization.writeMultimap(...)`\\n  - `Serialization.populateMultimap(...)`\\n  - key/value `ObjectOutputStream.writeObject(...)`\\n  - key/value `ObjectInputStream.readObject(...)`\\n- Added test Native Image reachability metadata:\\n  - `tests/src/org.glassfish.jersey.bundles.repackaged/jersey-guava/2.23.2/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/reachability-metadata.json`\\n- Updated existing scaffold test class to be `public` to satisfy the top-level test class rule:\\n  - `Jersey_guavaTest.java`\\n\\nPer instruction, I did not compile or run the tests.\", \"textSignature\": \"{\\\"v\\\":1,\\\"id\\\":\\\"msg_0cd3da9462914dcb0169f54172150481a284758c089909abc4\\\",\\\"phase\\\":\\\"final_answer\\\"}\"}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 489, \"output\": 1332, \"cacheRead\": 42496, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 44317, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"stop\", \"timestamp\": 1777680734319, \"responseId\": \"resp_0cd3da9462914dcb0169f5415eda0881a2bcc72a1649285ed2\"}}\n8624:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating ArrayList serialization**\\n\\nI'm wondering whether there's a need for `java.util.ArrayList` to be serializable. It seems like it might not be necessary, especially since the lists aren’t serialized by default. Instead, `Serialization.writeMultimap` only manually writes Strings. Plus, when it comes to deserialization, the ArrayList can just be created in the usual way. So, I think that serialization for ArrayList might not be needed after all.\\n\\n**Considering testing structure**\\n\\nIt seems like there's an expectation for a new test class related to scaffold, but I'm not sure. If I'm deleting something, there shouldn't be an active generic placeholder. The user asked to keep coverage for the active class in its own Java test file, so I think I shouldn't remove the generic element. Maybe the class name should be \\\"Serialization,\\\" leading to a file named \\\"SerializationTest.java.\\\" That seems like a good plan!\\n\\n**Evaluating test generation**\\n\\nIt seems that other active classes are getting tests, each having their own, while the existing Jersey_guavaTest isn’t created for the report class. I wonder if maybe the dynamic-access report could find the active class called `Serialization` and then generate a corresponding `SerializationTest`. That could be a good approach! I’ll need to finalize this thought.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0cd3da9462914dcb0169f5415f828081a2a8dd774ae45a2ca5\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp9UFyKJIwkYmu8701KFe8--TEmvRudwIK_qy2R3T-todVZYLucdcDmFu2acNNFLR3d3Gcza7P0Nuu9iTQanmnJmtRZrx_c4tyXxmVPd8QgrcWtejTaIQgoz6q0yVoZhzHgLmlJmWf71xxtDipdhNq58L5jtZ6vRHgRTnP5ZGghC7BVE_L_4uHYzWw4MlvG-puq8dSRvDMjRj35zsyq3WgjI_R6qqH_ewin7DQKB1XHu-5XmuL2Z24f045MD6PTnxX_pVqdNSo-RLPP82WA5DZ48FpPia74Hg3xYjNdzl2jKiTm442q1JczLcl3xhUolYt8OGubEVGvwg3e-XCGO7SCyb_2vb_8MrNg4OPtqUzwmF63mivS5w0PTI40SygoLiS23Tcal60gNxYGKU7OTWVShMzNgZHvSDgQpHF-WDkZLxapT_pcGHnsOgWRP9Ms8Ps-GarHDs2AEAHlMkKtzYgfuw-_olqH_E7UOymrRQV-0Vii7r5kCOSjv-ss2khT6hqXaLGSd2-utF8E7twdPPuRz4_D0GyDHH3iWxOG--wTt2tQ75qKbB3QnK6a9nP